Layering, positional matching, and inheritance

The standard ggplot template is not too onerous to write when creating a single geometric object. For example, a boxplot showing the distribution of weight measurements for each infant is created by

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = weight_kg, y = id))

However, when showing boxplots, it is usually good practice to also show the underlying data, especially when your data are small-ish. To do so, we layer on a call to geom_point:

ggplot(data = growth_data) + 
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = weight_kg, y = id)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = weight_kg, y = id))

The code starts to get a bit more complicated looking, and we can trim things down to make it cleaner. First, we can lean on three key facts: (i) the first argument of ggplot is data; (ii) the first argument of every geom_<GEOMNAME> is mapping; (iii) and the first and second arguments of aes are x and y, respectively.

Because of these key facts, we can use the R concept of positional matching, which allows you to specify arguments in their expected order without naming them. So, the code below is equivalent to the above code:

ggplot(growth_data) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(weight_kg, id)) +
  geom_point(aes(weight_kg, id))

In particular, we dont need data = in the call to ggplot because the data argument comes first, and therefore growth_data, which is now an unnamed argument, is matched to data by virtue of its position. The same principle applies to justify not needing to write mapping =, x =, and y =. The tradeoff from using positional matching is that you must be sure you have specified the arguments in the exact order that the function expects them. For example, aes(weight_kg, id) will give you a different result than aes(id, weight_kg): in the first case weight_kg is matched (and therefore mapped) to the x aesthetic, and in the second case weight_kg is matched and mapped to the y aesthetic.

Theres an additional way we can make this code even more concise using inheritance, which is a ggplot specific feature. Inheritance says that we can place inside of ggplot all elements of a plot that are intended to be shared in common by every layer. Referring to our figure, one shared element is data, and inheritance is already happening for this: the provided data object is silently passed down to and used by geom_boxplot and geom_point. Another shared element are the mapped aesthetics, as specified by aes(weight_kg, id). For this reason, the ggplot function has its own mapping argument (which is positioned second in the set of arguments), which, when specified, also gets passed down to the geoms.

Thus, the following code is also equivalent to all of the above code chunks:

ggplot(growth_data, aes(weight_kg, id)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_point()

Now, both the data argument (the first argument in our call to ggplot, by virtue of positional matching) and the mapping argument (the second argument, for the same reasons) get passed down to each of the geoms.

Inheritance is very flexible. If theres an aesthetic mapping that you want to apply to one geom, you can still incorporate it in the usual way without affeting the inheritance:

ggplot(growth_data, aes(weight_kg, id)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_label(aes(label = months))

In the above plot, the points are labeled according the value of months. You can also overwrite an aesthetic that would otherwise be inherited from ggplot.

The scale family of functions

Please note that in the remaining sections of this independent guide, we will still cover all of the same topics discussed in the corresponding guideded practice but with slightly different examples.

The code below creates several plots. We first create a plot showing individual pairs of height-weight measurements, using different colors for each infant id. We then layer on the infant-specific height-weight trajectories. We have done so while taking full advantage of positional matching and inheritance, but we also use a novel feature that weve previously not used:

weight_versus_height <- 
  ggplot(growth_data, aes(weight_kg, height_cm, color = id)) + 
  geom_point()

weight_versus_height

Weve first assigned the output from ggplot to an object named weight_versus_height. The plot isnt shown when we make the assignment, but if we type the name of the object in the console and press enter, we view the plot. It is the base plot showing just the points.

weight_versus_height +
  geom_line(aes(color = id))

With this plot object created, we can extend it by adding on other ggplot features before printing, as you can see in the chunk above. Specifically, weve layered on a call to geom_line to show the trajectories.

To make the variable labels more informative, we use the scale_<AESTHETIC>_continous and scale_<AESTHETIC>_discrete families of functions. Every aesthetic has its own set of scale functions. Within these functions, we can modify the way in which the aesthetic is visualized and presented. So, for example, to change the labels, we would write the following:

weight_versus_height + 
  geom_line() +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Height (cm)") +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Weight (kg)") +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "ID")

These scale features are added to the base plot just like other functions in ggplot2. We have to use the continuous versions of these scale functions for the x and y aesthetics because they are doubles, whereas we have to use the discrete version for the color aesthetic, because the id variable is a character.

The quoted names can be whatever you choose. Take care in writing out these aesthetic names. If you accidentally switch the values of the name argument for the x and y aesthetics, the labels of the x-axis the y-axis will be switched, and the plot will be misleading.

The scale family of functions allows for other useful modifications of your plot. A common example is to change the number or nature of the tick marks along an axis.

weight_versus_height +
  geom_line() +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Height (cm)", 
                     breaks = seq(from = 48, to = 58, by = 2)) +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Weight (kg)") +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "ID")

Here I am using a function from base R called seq, which is used to create a sequence of numbers stored as a vector. In this case, Im creating a vector that starts at 48, increments by 2 at a time, and continues on in this manner until it would go beyond a number larger than 58, stopping just before this point.

You can alternatively use the concatenate function, c(), to provide a custom set of breaks, as in:

weight_versus_height +
  geom_line() +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Height (cm)", 
                     breaks = c(50, 51, 53, 57)) +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Weight (kg)") +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "ID")

You can also use the scale functions to extend the limits of your aesthetics using the limits argument. This is most intuitively demonstrated by extending the x- or y-axes. For example, smallest and largest weight measurements are 2.9kg and 6.6kg, respectively, and ggplot will automatically set the limits of the x-axis to go just a little bit beyond these most extreme values. We can specify that the limits should instead be 2.5kg and 7.5kg as follows:

weight_versus_height +
  geom_line() +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Height (cm)") +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Weight (kg)", 
                     limits = c(2.5, 7.5)) +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "ID")

Relative to the base plot, the x-axis is stretched out a bit further on either side.

To see what other features of an aesthetic you can modify with the scale family of functions, you should inspect the help page, e.g.?scale_x_continuous.

If you only need to change the labels of aesthetics and nothing else, there is a shortcut function provided called labs:

weight_versus_height +
  geom_line() +
  labs(y = "Height (cm)", 
       x = "Weight (kg)",
       color = "ID")

facet_grid and facet_wrap

Faceting uses the idea of small multiples to show data across time or space. Faceting is sort of like another aesthetic, allowing you to show your data across multiple panels. To highlight how to facet as well as to demonstrate that we can add any ggplot function to an existing plot (and not just scale or geom_ functions as above), run the following code:

weight_versus_height + 
  facet_grid(rows = vars(months))

As an aside: this code will only run if you created the weight_versus_height object as we did above. Otherwise, you will get an error message from R that states

## Error: object 'weight_versus_height' not found

Here we have taken our base plot of weight versus height, which we created earlier, and added instructions to plot each id separately. The vars function acts similarly to the aes function and should contain the name or names of variables that we wish to facet by, separated by commas. The rows argument in facet_grid means that each unique combination of the variables in vars will get its own row. To facet by columns, we would use the following:

weight_versus_height + 
  facet_grid(cols = vars(months))

Save your script once again before closing.
